We further demonstrated the capability and performance of SE-CDs for bioimaging. SE-CDs (200μg/ml: 1/5 dilution) were delivered into SK-Hep-1 cells for 24h using lipofectamin as a carrier (Sells et al., 1995). As shown in Fig. 4
                        , the cells clearly exhibited blue, green, and red fluorescence in Fig. 4b, c and d, respectively. We can see in the images that the SE-CDs were internalized into the cells. To demonstrate the use of SE-CDs for bioimaging, SK-Hep-1 cells were incubated with SE-CDs (200μg/ml: 1/5 dilution) for 24h. The fluorescence images (Fig. 5
                        ) associated with the SE-CDs exhibit strongly blue (f), green (j), and red (n) fluorescence, which was localized in the cell membrane and cytoplasm of the SK-Hep-1 cells. In contrast, the plasmid DNA-encoded green and red fluorescence proteins, pEGFP and pDsRed, exhibited only bright green (Fig. 5k) and red (Fig. 5p) fluorescence, and their transfection efficiency was inconsistent. These results demonstrate that SE-CDs exhibit multicolor fluorescence rather than the single fluorescence characteristic of traditional fluorescent proteins. Finally, cellular internalization of SE-CDs confirms their potential for applications in biological labelling and imaging.
